<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-05-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-05-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="368" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d368">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/1777½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the Counselor for the Department of State</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Lansing</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-05-20">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 20, 1915</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Lansing</hi>: May I not thank you very
                            warmly for your kindness in sending me an amplified copy of your
                                suggestions<note n="74" xml:id="d368fn1">Letter of May 17, 1915,
                                    <ref target="#pg_407">p. 407</ref>.</note> as to alternative
                            courses of action should the Imperial German Government not respond as
                            we hope it will to our note? I shall keep this by me.</p>
                        <p>Cordially and sincerely yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Woodrow Wilson</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>